  "text": "Kafka's log compaction architecture is implemented through a set of Java classes in the storage module. The core components are:\n\n**1. Cleaner Thread (LogCleaner.java):** The LogCleaner class is the main entry point for log compaction, implementing BrokerReconfigurable. It manages a pool of background CleanerThread instances (nested inner class that extends ShutdownableThread). Each CleanerThread continuously runs the doWork() method, which calls tryCleanFilthiestLog() and eventually cleanFilthiestLog() to perform log cleaning operations. The LogCleaner class is responsible for thread pool management, metrics collection, and configuration management.\n\n**2. Segment Selection Policy (LogCleanerManager.java):** LogCleanerManager implements the segment/log selection policy through the grabFilthiestCompactedLog() method. This method selects which log partition to clean next by computing a \"dirtiness\" ratio (the ratio of cleanable bytes to total bytes). It filters logs based on:\n   - Whether they have compact retention policy enabled\n   - Whether they are not already being cleaned\n   - Whether they meet the minimum cleanable ratio threshold (minCleanableRatio from LogConfig)\n   - Compaction lag timing constraints (min and max compaction lag)\n\nThe method uses a Comparator to find the \"filthiest\" log (highest cleanable ratio) and returns it as a LogToClean object. It also calculates cleanable offsets through the cleanableOffsets() method, which determines the first dirty offset and first uncleanable offset for each log.\n\n**3. Key-based Deduplication Logic (Cleaner.java with OffsetMap and SkimpyOffsetMap):** The actual key deduplication is implemented in the Cleaner class, which uses an OffsetMap (interface) backed by SkimpyOffsetMap (implementation). SkimpyOffsetMap is a memory-efficient hash table that:\n   - Uses MD5 cryptographic hashing as a proxy for keys to save space\n   - Stores key hashes and offset values in a ByteBuffer\n   - Implements